Rating: 4
This is a fabulous dish! Incredibly easy, richly flavorful, impressive presentation - it doesn't get much better than this. I'll attempt to consolidate the advice of previous reviewers, as well as my own discoveries in making this dish several times myself. 1) Like almost every reviewer before me suggests, at LEAST double if not triple the spinach. Those who cook with fresh spinach know that it cooks down dramatically. I used a 9-oz bag for just two of us, and we ate every bite. 2) Double the sauce. Keep the amounts of the sauce ingredients consistent - don't just double the liquid, but double also the tarragon, shallots, etc. 3) Use fresh tarragon. Dried tarragon has a completely different flavor - not nearly as rich or pleasing. 4) Be careful not to overcook the salmon. The recipe says 4 min. per side on med-high - I prefer 2 to 3 min. per side on high, depending on the thickness. This gives you a nice crispy surface, while leaving the interior melt-in-your-mouth tender. Remember that it will cook a bit more on its own after removing from the pan - plus, you'll be heating it up once more in the sauce at the end - so it's better to slightly undercook than overcook. 5) It will take longer than 3 minutes for the sauce to thicken - it took mine 5 to 6. 6) The wine matters! Use a decent dry white wine with some body to it. I used a good, oaky Napa chardonnay. Remember the old adage - never cook with a wine you wouldn't drink! By increasing the spinach enough, you really don't need to serve another vegetable. Add a carb of your choice - I've tried mashed potatoes, orzo, and brown rice. We preferred the brown rice, pouring some of the sauce over it, which produced an incredible earthy blend of flavors along with the pleasing al-dente bite of the rice. Serve with the remainder of your nice oaky chardonnay, and you've got a dish that will impress even the most discriminating dinner-party guests!

